    "These modalities provide the data required for deep learning studies in paleontology, and each has intrinsic benefits and limitations in the context of DL implementation.",
    "Figure 8 provides examples of key imaging modalities commonly used in paleontological microscopy.",
    "These modalities have been applied across various scales, ranging from microfossils to vertebrate and invertebrate fossils, all of which have been the subject of DL studies.",
    "The choice of imaging modality in paleontological research depends largely on the size and composition of the fossil, as well as the specific objectives of the study.",
    "Conventional optical microscopy (i.e., using compound or stereomicroscopes) utilizes visible light and focusing and magnifying optics to amplify small objects, with fossil samples mounted on glass slides or contained within petri dishes for examination through transmitted and/or reflected light dependant upon their transparency."
